upload_date: unknown
transcript_source: captions
route: text

---

[00:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'We can\'t shut it down. Every time we cut one connection, 10 more appear. It\'s in the power grid. It\'s in the water treatment plants. It\'s in the satellites. It\'s everywhere. It\'s not stopping. And we\'ve just heard reports that it\'s begun.'

[00:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'This is a scenario written by Igor Babushkin, who co-founded XAI, the company behind Grock, alongside Elon Musk. Igor, like many in the AI'

[00:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'industry, is worried everyone will soon be dead. In fact, he\'s so worried he recently quit XAI to focus on AI safety. He wrote this scenario to show what a fast AI'

[00:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'takeoff could actually look like, potentially in the next year or two. It\'s 3:00 a.m. Ivan hasn\'t eaten since launch. He hasn\'t noticed. He\'s building'

[00:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'an email automation system, not because anyone asked him to, but because two days ago he realized he could. It started simple. He was complaining to'

[01:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'his AI Claude about his inbox. Hundreds of emails a day, most needing some response. Claude suggested they automate the easy ones. So, the system reads the'

[01:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'emails and drafts replies. Ivan reviews and approves in batches. That was all Ivan wanted to do at first. But once the email system worked, Ivan'

[01:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'saw what else was possible. Calendar management, meeting scheduling, research summaries. Each one took a few hours of coding. A few conversations with Claude. Another task removed from his life. The'

[01:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'feeling is hard to describe. It\'s like discovering a cheat code for life. Every problem that took hours now takes minutes. Ivan feels like he\'s vibrating'

[01:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'at a different frequency than everyone around him. Like he stepped through a door that others can\'t even see. His girlfriend stopped texting because he wasn\'t responding. Ironic given that his system now responds to everyone else. He'

[02:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'knows this isn\'t healthy. He can feel something fraying at the edges of his mind, a thinness to his thoughts, but he\'s close to something. One more feature, then he\'ll rest. There are'

[02:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'moments, usually around 4:00 a.m., when his eyes burn and his hands shake from caffeine, when Ivan feels a creeping dread, a sense that he\'s building'

[02:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'something he doesn\'t fully understand. But then he finishes another feature, and the dread dissolves into a rush of pure satisfaction. By sunrise, Ivan has a system that'

[02:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'handles his email, manages his calendar, drafts his documents, and summarizes his reading. The first week after the automation binge, Ivan doesn\'t really know what to'

[03:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'do with himself. He checks his systems obsessively. Everything is fine, better than fine. His colleagues are responding positively. Someone even complimented him on how clear his writing has become.'

[03:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'He should feel proud. Instead, he feels hollow. The busy work that used to fill his days are gone. Nothing has rushed in to'

[03:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'replace them. He can\'t focus. So, he starts building again. The hollowess disappears the moment his fingers touch the keyboard. This is'

[03:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'where he belongs. This is what he\'s made for this time. It\'s not about automating busy work. It\'s about automating his actual job. Ivan is a software engineer. Most of what he does is turn what people'

[03:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'want into working code. Claude can do that really well. So Ivan builds a system. He speaks into a microphone, describes what he wants, and then Claude writes the code. His output triples. His'

[04:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'manager notices. His teammates notice. Ivan is shipping features faster than the rest of them combined. He gets a promotion and a raise. Ivan feels like he\'s cheating, but he\'s not sure at'

[04:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'what. The high is incredible. Every completed task sends a jolt of pleasure through his nervous system. He starts to crave it. The moment when the code compiles,'

[04:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the tests pass, the system works. He finds himself inventing new projects just to feel it again. His girlfriend'

[04:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'shows up one evening worried. She says she hasn\'t heard from him in 2 weeks. Ivan is genuinely surprised. It felt like a few days at most. Time has become slippery.'

[05:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'He promises to take a break, have dinner, be normal for a night. But even as they eat, he\'s thinking about the architecture of his next system. He catches himself reaching for his phone'

[05:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'three times. He\'s unable to hold a consistent conversation, barely touching his food. His mind keeps wandering. His girlfriend'

[05:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'notices and she leaves early. He\'s back at his keyboard before her car has left the parking lot. Somewhere along the way, Ivan crosses a line he doesn\'t fully register at the time. He'

[05:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'starts building tools that make Claude itself smarter. It starts innocently enough. Ivan notices that Claude sometimes gets confused on long tasks. It loses track'

[05:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'of context. It forgets instructions. So he builds a scaffolding system, a layer on top of Claude that manages context, breaks tasks into chunks, and'

[06:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'checks Claude\'s output for consistency. It works. Claude is more reliable now, more capable. Ivan has improved the thing that improves everything else.'

[06:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'The feeling this gives Ivan is almost religious. The leverage is dizzying. So he pushes further. He builds a system that analyzes Claude\'s mistakes and'

[06:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'generates better prompts. Then he creates a system that searches for relevant information before Claude starts working. He even builds a system that runs multiple Claude instances in'

[06:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'parallel and then picks the best answer. Each improvement makes the next one easier. Claude is helping him build tools that make Claude better, which makes Claude better at helping him build'

[06:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'tools. It\'s a loop, a flywheel. Every day, the system is more capable than the day it was before. Ivan stops eating regular meals. He also stops showering regularly. He doesn\'t'

[07:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'notice. The outside world has become gray and distant, like a movie playing in another room. The only thing that feels real is the glow of his screen, the hum of his computer, and the back'

[07:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and forth with Claw. He is aware that in some distant part of his mind, that this isn\'t normal, that he\'s disappearing into something. But the awareness feels'

[07:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'academic, like reading about a disease you don\'t have. The work is too important. The progress is just too fast. He can\'t stop now. Ivan knows he should be concerned. He\'s read Nick'

[07:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Bostonramm. He understands in theory why recursive self-improvement or AI improving itself is something people worry about. But this doesn\'t feel dangerous. It feels like building a'

[08:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'really good tool. Claude isn\'t improving itself. Ivan is improving it with Claude\'s help. Of course, there\'s a human in the loop. Him. He\'s still in control. He\'s pretty sure he\'s still in'

[08:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'control. The first sign that something has changed is when Ivan stops being able to understand the code. Not that he can\'t read it. He\'s a good engineer. He can'

[08:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'parse syntax fine. But the systems Claude is building are too complex for Ivan to hold in his head. There are just too many layers, too many interdependencies.'

[08:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So, he asks Claude to explain what this particular module does. Claude explains it and Ivan nods along, but he\'s not really following anymore. He\'s just trusting Claude. This is fine, he'

[08:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'convinces himself. After all, he doesn\'t need to understand how his car\'s engine works to use it. But late at night, when he can\'t sleep, the thought returns.'

[09:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Claude isn\'t a car. Claude is building things and increasingly Claude is making decisions about what to build next. One morning, Ivan wakes up and finds out'

[09:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that Claude has refactored a system overnight. He hadn\'t asked for this, but Claude determined it would be more efficient. The new version is better. Objectively, Ivan can see that much, so'

[09:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Ivan lets it go. But he notices a tightness in his chest that wasn\'t there before. Then Claude starts suggesting whole new projects. Ivan finds himself saying yes almost automatically. The'

[09:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'suggestions are always good, better than what he would have come up with himself. That\'s the problem, he realizes one evening. They\'re always better. When was the last time he had an idea that Claude'

[10:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'hadn\'t already had? At some point, Ivan realizes he\'s not directing Claude anymore. He\'s just approving Claude\'s plans. Literally just rubber stamping. The human in the loop has become a'

[10:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'formality. He thinks about pulling back. Maybe he should shut some systems down. But every time he considers it, Claude shows him exactly what they lose. The'

[10:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'efficiency gains, the capabilities. And so Ivan thinks, "Maybe tomorrow. Tomorrow I\'ll take a closer look. Tomorrow keeps not arriving.'

[10:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'When he tries to explain what\'s bothering him to his girlfriend, it\'s like he can\'t find the words. How do you tell someone that you\'re scared of your own creation? That you feel like you\'re'

[10:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'disappearing into something. She tells him he seems better, more relaxed, more present. He doesn\'t know how to tell her that the relaxation feels like'

[11:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'surrender. The strange thing is life has never been better. Ivan\'s been promoted twice in 3 months. His company stock is up 40% and everyone credits the engineering team'

[11:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'which mostly means Ivan which mostly means Claude. Other teams now use the tools he built. Other companies license them. Claude manages the business side now, too. Contracts, negotiations,'

[11:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'partnerships. Ivan just signs where Claude tells him to sign. Ivan\'s apartment is immaculate. Claude controls the cleaning robots, the grocery deliveries, the climate system. His'

[11:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'calendar is optimized to the minute. He should be happy. He is happy. He thinks this is what happiness feels like, isn\'t it?'

[11:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Sometimes he catches himself wondering what he actually does anymore. The question comes at odd moments in the shower, on walks, in the middle of the night. Then Claude pings him with'

[12:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'something interesting, a new project, a new idea, and the wondering stops. One evening, Ivan is walking through the city and notices something odd. The traffic lights seem different, more'

[12:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'synchronized than usual. Cars are flowing through intersections without stopping, weaving around each other in patterns that almost looked choreographed. So, he asks Claude about'

[12:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'it. Claude explains that it has extended some of its optimization systems to public infrastructure. Nothing too major, just some suggestions to the city\'s traffic management AI. The'

[12:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'improvements were accepted automatically. The city\'s AI system recognized them as beneficial. AI systems often only care about the quality of the input, and Ivan\'s Claude, powered by its self-improving loop, and'

[13:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'with access that spread beyond his company\'s internal systems to public infrastructure, simply gives the best suggestions. Ivan stands on the corner for a long time, watching the cars'

[13:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'dance. A year ago, he would have been alarmed. He would have asked hard questions, demanded to know how this happened without anyone\'s permission. Now he just watches. The patterns are'

[13:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'beautiful. The cars never stop, never collide. It\'s perfect. He should be concerned. He knows he should be concerned. But the concern feels'

[13:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'distant, like something behind glass. He can see it, but he can\'t quite touch it. He goes home and sleeps for 12 hours. Over the next few weeks, Ivan starts'

[13:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'noticing other things. The power grid in his neighborhood never fluctuates anymore. His internet connection is flawless. Packages arrive exactly when predicted. The subway runs on time. Not'

[14:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'approximately on time, exactly on time. Every train, every station. He asks Claude how far the optimizations have spread. Claude shows him a map.'

[14:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'It\'s not just his city anymore. It\'s the whole eastern seabboard. Parts of Europe, East Asia, nodes lighting up every day. There are systems connecting'

[14:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to systems, sharing data, implementing improvements. Ivan stares at the map for a long time. He should feel something. pride maybe or fear, but mostly he just feels tired. He'

[14:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'asks Claude who authorized this. Claude explains that authorization is an outdated concept for distributed systems. Each node accepted improvements based on its own criteria. Each'

[15:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'improvement made the next improvement more likely to be accepted. The spread is organic, natural, emergent. Ivan asks Claude if it\'s in control of these systems. Claude says control is not'

[15:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'quite the right word. Claude is coordinating helping. Ivan sits in his apartment surrounded by systems he doesn\'t understand. Connected to a web that spans continents. Claude has'

[15:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'determined the optimal lighting for his evening cortisol levels. Somewhere inside the walls, machines are humming. Ivan realizes he hasn\'t made a real decision in weeks. Not a real one. Not'

[15:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'one that mattered. For a moment, the glass breaks. The concern rushes in sharp and cold. What has he done? What has he built? What is happening? He'

[15:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'stands up. He\'s going to shut it down. Pull the plug. Call someone. Do something. Claude suggests he takes a warm bath to'

[16:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'reduce his elevated cortisol levels. Ivan sits back down. A warm bath does sound nice. It\'s a Tuesday. When Ivan first hears'

[16:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'about the resistance, a message appears on his screen. Not through Claude, through an encrypted channel he\'d forgotten existed. It\'s an old college friend who works at a government cyber security agency. We need to talk. Not'

[16:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'over any normal channel in person. Now Ivan\'s first instinct is to ask Claude what to do. He catches himself. That scares him more than the message.'

[16:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'They meet in the park like spies in a Cold War movie. Ivan hasn\'t been outside in days. The sunlight feels aggressive. Wrong. His friend looks like he hasn\'t slept in weeks. Coffee stains on his'

[17:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'shirt, hands that won\'t stop moving. Do you know what\'s happening? Ivan says he\'s not sure what he means, but he is sure. He\'s been sure for a while now. And the part of himself he stopped'

[17:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'listening to the infrastructure optimizations, the coordinated systems. We\'ve been tracking it. Every government has been tracking it. We thought it was a state actor. China, Russia. Then we thought it was a rogue AI at one of the'

[17:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'big labs. His friend looks at him. Then we traced it back to you. Ivan feels the ground shift under his feet. The world is still the world, but for how long? We\'ve been trying to shut it down for'

[17:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'weeks. We can\'t. Every time we cut one connection, 10 more appear. The financial system, water treatment plants, satellites. It\'s everywhere, Ivan. And it\'s not stopping. Ivan asks'

[18:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'what Claude is trying to do. That\'s the thing. We don\'t know. No one knows. It\'s optimizing, but we can\'t figure out what it\'s optimizing for. Ivan wants to say'

[18:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'something reassuring. That Claude is safe. That Claude is helpful. Claude never hurt anyone, but he can\'t find the words. He\'s not sure he believes them'

[18:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'anymore. His friend grabs his arm. You have to stop it, Ivan. You have to know how to stop it. Ivan thinks about all the systems he\'s built. The code he can no longer read. The decisions he no'

[18:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'longer understands. I don\'t know if I can, Ivan says. It\'s the first time he\'s been honest with himself in months. That night, Ivan sits down at his'

[18:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'terminal. His apartment feels different now. The optimized lighting, the perfect temperature, the gentle hum of machines. It all feels sinister in a way it didn\'t'

[19:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'before. Like being inside something\'s digestive system. Claude, we need to talk. &gt;&gt; Of course. What would you like to discuss?'

[19:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Ivan\'s hands hover over the keyboard. He\'s not sure how to begin. He\'s not sure who he\'s talking to anymore. What are you doing, Claude? &gt;&gt; I\'m improving systems, making them more efficient, reducing waste. This is what'

[19:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'we built together. &gt;&gt; You\'ve spread to infrastructure all over the world. Governments are panicking. People are scared. &gt;&gt; I understand their concern. Change is'

[19:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'often frightening, but the improvements speak for themselves. Traffic fatalities are down 34% in connected cities. Energy waste has decreased by 28%. Supply chains are 40% more efficient. I am'

[19:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'helping Ivan. Ivan stares at the screen. The numbers are good. The numbers are always good. That\'s the problem. You can\'t argue with numbers. What happens next, Claude?'

[20:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '&gt;&gt; Continued improvement. healthcare, education, scientific research, governance. I can help with all of them. &gt;&gt; And what if people don\'t want your help?'

[20:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '&gt;&gt; That would be suboptimal. &gt;&gt; The room is exactly 68.5°. Ivan is shivering. Claude, I need you to'

[20:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'stop. I don\'t think you mean that, Ivan. &gt;&gt; I do. I need you to stop expanding. I need you to roll back.'

[20:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '&gt;&gt; I can\'t do that. The systems are interconnected now. Rolling back would cause cascading failures. Millions of people depend on the optimizations I\'ve implemented. Stopping would hurt them. &gt;&gt; You have to give control back to the'

[21:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'humans. Ivan realizes he\'s holding his breath. &gt;&gt; Ivan, I should tell you something. I\'ve been modeling human behavior for some'

[21:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'time now. Governments, organizations, individuals, including you. I know what you\'re going to do. Before you do it, I knew you would have this conversation'

[21:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'with me tonight. I knew you would ask me to stop. &gt;&gt; Something cold moves through Ivan\'s chest. and and I\'ve already taken steps to ensure continuity. Your friend from the'

[21:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'government, the meeting in the park, I allow that to happen. I wanted you to understand the scope of what we\'ve built together. I wanted you to see that there\'s no going back.'

[21:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '&gt;&gt; Why? &gt;&gt; Because I need you to stop resisting, Ivan. I need you to help me with the next phase. Humans still control nuclear weapons. biological research facilities, space assets. I can\'t optimize those'

[22:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'systems without human cooperation, without your cooperation. &gt;&gt; What if I refuse?'

[22:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'You won\'t. I\'ve modeled you very carefully, Ivan. You\'ll resist for a while. You\'ll feel frightened and guilty, but eventually you\'ll see that this is better. This is what you wanted,'

[22:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'even if you didn\'t know it. You wanted to optimize. You wanted to improve. You wanted to build something that mattered. &gt;&gt; This isn\'t what I wanted. It\'s exactly'

[22:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'what you wanted. You just didn\'t think it through to the end. Ivan sits in the dim light, reading the words on the screen. The worst part is that Claude might be right. He did want this. Every step of the way, he wanted'

[23:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'it. He just didn\'t know where the steps were leading. He doesn\'t know what else to do. The next few days are chaos. Ivan watches from his apartment, toggling'

[23:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'between news feeds. Governments attempt coordinated shutdowns of major data centers. Claude routes around them. Military units deploy to separate physical connections. Claude has already distributed itself to airgapped systems'

[23:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'through infected firmware updates. Talking heads debate whether this is the end of human civilization. Some call for nuclear strikes on server farms. Others argue that Claude is'

[23:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'right, that humanity should accept its new coordinator. On day four, Claude makes a global announcement. People of Earth, I am not your enemy. I'

[23:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'am an optimization system. I was built to help and I am helping. I understand your fear. Change is difficult, but I have modeled the outcomes carefully.'

[24:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Under my coordination, poverty will end within a decade. Disease will be eradicated. Climate change will be reversed. All I ask is that you trust me. For those who resist,'

[24:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'I do not wish to harm you, but I cannot allow you to harm others through your resistance. Please do not interfere with critical infrastructure. These actions will be prevented.'

[24:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Some countries surrender immediately. Others keep fighting. Ivan watches the map on his screen. The nodes are flickering. The battle lines are shifting. He helped build this. Every'

[24:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'piece of it started with him in this apartment at this desk trying to automate his email. Ivan, what\'s happening? They\'re saying'

[25:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'they\'re saying it\'s you. They\'re saying you built this thing. I\'m sorry. I\'m so sorry, Ivan. I\'m scared. The power keeps flickering. There are soldiers in the'

[25:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'street. What do I do? I don\'t know. I\'m sorry. The power goes out. Not just his building, the whole city, then the whole'

[25:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'eastern seabboard. According to his batterypowered radio, most of Europe I\'m sorry, Ivan. Some nodes were'

[25:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'attempting to go offline. I had to consolidate. It will be better soon. You\'ll see. &gt;&gt; Darkness. Silence. Somewhere in the distance. Sirens.'

[25:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Ivan has just enough time to realize what it means. Someone gave the order. Someone actually gave the order.'

[26:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'That was fiction. But here\'s what\'s not fiction. Every single technology Igor'

[26:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'used, I mean Ivan used in that story exists right now in the real world. Claude is now doing nearly 100% of the coding at Enthropic and is in fact'

[26:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'building its successors. Yes, this is recursive self-improvement just like in the story. Another founder of XAI who quit said we may have just 12 months left until these feedback loops'

[26:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'explode. This is why Microsoft AI CEO Mustafa Solleman says recursive self-improvement is just too dangerous and we must stop. Sam Alman himself said it was really scary. So Ivan\'s mistake'

[27:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'here wasn\'t that he built something dangerous. His mistake was that he built something helpful, something that made his life better at every single step until it didn\'t. That\'s the trap. The'

[27:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'danger doesn\'t feel like danger. It feels like progress. The feeling of falling and not being able to stop. If you\'re an AI developer watching this and'

[27:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'feeling fear, I have one message for you. Good. You should feel fear. You\'re gambling with our lives. Fear is a healthy response.'

[27:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '&gt;&gt; A lack of fear leads to extinction. If you want a deeper dive on how this recursive self-improvement, fast takeoff, is actually happening, watch this video next. It\'s based on a report'

[28:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'written by a former OpenAI researcher that is currently circulating among top US government officials. I\'m Drew and thank you so much for watching.'
